{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d77f359c-f448-4864-8f39-9937934988cb","content":"This is an **xUnit v3** project on **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (MTP). Use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThis matches all tests whose fully qualified name contains `ShoppingCartTests`, which filters to just that class. The `~` operator means \"contains\".","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"57cb6bb5-c366-463b-aa28-ce8314d96bde","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is an xUnit v3 project with `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to true, meaning it uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). The namespace is `Contoso.Cart.Tests` and the class is `ShoppingCartTests`, so the fully qualified class name is `Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests`.\n\nFor MTP with xUnit v3, the filter syntax uses `--filter` with the MTP filter format. For xUnit v3 on MTP, the filter syntax to filter by class is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"Type=Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests\"\n\n\n```\n\nActually, I need to reconsider this. With xUnit v3 on MTP, the filter properties work differently—xUnit v3 supports its own `--treenode-filter` syntax, or I can use the standard MTP `--filter` with properties like `FullyQualifiedName`. Since `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is true, `dotnet test` delegates to MTP, so the standard MTP filter for the class name would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName=Contoso.Cart.Tests.ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nOr using a contains pattern:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ShoppingCartTests\"\n```\n\nThe second approach is safer since it matches any test whose fully qualified name contains \"ShoppingCartTests\". For xUnit v3 on MTP, I could also use `--treenode-filter` with a tree node pattern, though the `FullyQualifiedName` approach is more straightforward.","outputTokens":628,"requestId":"1BC4:F3EF4:22B3E81:2653D42:6A03D60E"},"id":"c11f3531-a162-46d5-ade8-2c767ccd91ae","